description:
## Severity
Minor
## Dimension
error-handling
## Location
src/skills.rs:37-55
## Violation
The parser slices the string by raw byte indices computed from `find`. If a multi-byte character lies on the boundary, the indexing panics. Quoted lines:

    if !content.starts_with("---") {
        return None;
    }
    let rest = &content[3..];
    let end = rest.find("---")?;
    let frontmatter = rest[..end].trim();
    let body = rest[end + 3..].trim();

`&content[3..]` is safe (3 ASCII dashes) but `rest[end + 3..]` is only safe if the three bytes following `end` are also ASCII. In a malformed file the `find("---")` byte offset can sit before non-ASCII content (e.g. `---\n…\n---𠮷` or a corrupt mixed-encoding payload), splitting a codepoint and triggering an str-slice panic that takes down the whole REPL.
## Mandated refactor
Use a YAML-frontmatter crate (gray_matter, yaml-front-matter). If a hand-rolled parser is kept, switch to `str::char_indices` to locate the closing `---` and use `str::get(end+3..)` so a malformed boundary returns None instead of panicking. Add a fuzz test with non-ASCII payloads.
